===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|sēam}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*saumaz||that which is sewn}}. Cognate with West Frisian {{term|seam|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|zoom|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Saum|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|söm|lang=sv}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|sewing|lang=en}} A [[folded]] back and [[stitch]]ed piece of [[fabric]]; especially, the stitching that joins two or more pieces of fabric.
# A [[suture]].
# A thin [[stratum]], especially of [[coal]] or [[mineral]].
# {{context|cricket|lang=en}} The stitched [[equatorial]] seam of a [[cricket ball]]; the [[sideways]] [[movement]] of a ball when it [[bounce]]s on the seam.
# An old English [[measure]] of [[grain]], containing eight [[bushel]]s.
# An old English measure of [[glass]], containing twenty-four [[wey]]s of five [[pound]]s, or 120 pounds.
#* '''1952''': As white glass was 6s. the 'seam', containing 24 'weys' (pise, or pondera) of 5 lb., and 2 1/2 lb. was reckoned sufficient to make one foot of glazing, the cost of glass would be 1 1/2d. leaving 2 1/2d. for labour. &mdash; [[w:en:Louis Francis Salzman|L. F. Salzman|]], ''Building in England'', p. 175.
# {{context|construction|lang=en}} A joint formed by mating two separate sections of materials.
#: '''''Seams''' can be made or sealed in a variety of ways, including adhesive bonding, hot-air welding, solvent welding, using adhesive tapes, sealant, etc.''
# A line or depression left by a cut or wound; a [[scar]]; a [[cicatrix]].
# {{context|figurative|lang=en}} A line of junction; a joint.
#* Addison
#*: Precepts should be so finely wrought together {{...}} that no coarse '''seam''' may discover where they join.

